ng back and forth in history. Together the modernist time-obsession and the fantasy of moving in time help us to rethink the shapes of time, the consistency of timespace and the nature of history.Key FeaturesDraws on insights from a range of sources, including critical geography, postcolonial theory, science and technology studies and time studiesExamines different kinds of objects together: SF, Impressionism, and Henri Lefebvre’s rhythmanalysis; evolutionary biology, Eliot’s The Waste Land, and Leinster’s Sidewise in Time"; Woolf, Philip K. Dick’s alternate history, and the films Interstellar and Tree of Life"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aScience fiction, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aScience fiction, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aTime in literature. 0aTime travel in literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z97831107804200 cprintz978147443133040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781474431354?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474431354423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474431354/original  a978-3-11-078042-0  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK